bullets that opened

21:16.509 --> 21:18.210 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
these holes in the door.

21:18.244 --> 21:23.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LULU GARCIA-NAVARRO: Innocent
bystanders are
being killed almost every day in
Rio. But

21:23.916 --> 21:28.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
police too are dying in large
numbers, as
the battle over territory
continues.

21:28.888 --> 21:33.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On our way to film with Carol
that morning,
we heard of another casualty. We
drove to

21:33.792 --> 21:43.702 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the funeral later that day.

21:43.736 --> 21:48.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Police officer Eduardo Dias had
been killed
the day before, shot by gang
members as he

21:48.307 --> 21:53.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was leaving his UPP post.
According to the
police, he was killed on this
street in front

21:53.646 --> 21:58.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the Mangueira favela, and in
plain view
of the Maracana Stadium, site of
the Olympics

21:58.484 --> 22:03.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
opening ceremony in August. A
police pastor
at the funeral addressed the
crowd.

22:03.889 --> 22:10.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Until when, dear lord, will we
have to bury
our good cops? Until when will
we bury our

22:10.996 --> 22:15.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
children, our parents with young
kids? Do
not forget the military police
in your prayers.

22:15.968 --> 22:18.604 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Pray for us all," he said.

22:18.637 --> 22:25.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So far this year, 41 police have
been killed
in Rio state. Murders generally
are up 15

22:25.678 --> 22:31.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
percent in the city, robberies
up 30 percent.
There is a sense here that
things are spiraling

22:31.350 --> 22:33.185 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out of control.

22:33.219 --> 22:39.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just last week, a 16-year-old
girl was allegedly
gang-raped in a Rio favela by as
many as 30

22:39.158 --> 22:46.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
men. Two boys, 14 and 16, were
tortured and
murdered by gang members in
another city over

22:46.098 --> 22:52.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the bay. Both were documented on
social media
and spread widely around Brazil.

22:52.037 --> 22:56.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those who study pacification say
it's too
early to conclude whether it has
failed. But

22:56.942 --> 22:58.844 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
many mistakes have been made.

22:58.877 --> 23:04.483 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
IGNACIO CANO, Rio State
University: For many
of us, the hope was that UPPs
would help transform

23:04.516 --> 23:10.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the public security paradigm and
the police.
And, unfortunately, this is the
area in which

23:10.055 --> 23:15.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the advance has been more
modest, to say it
gently.

23:15.427 --> 23:20.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LULU GARCIA-NAVARRO: Ignacio
Cano is a professor
from Rio State University's
Laboratory on

23:20.099 --> 23:25.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Violence. He says police in Rio
are still
some of the most brutal in the
world, responsible

23:25.471 --> 23:30.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for 20 percent of the homicides
in the city,
according to Amnesty
International.

23:30.909 --> 23:35.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Police officials have continued
to defend
pacification. They blame drastic
budget cuts

23:35.681 --> 23:41.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for many of the problems.
Colonel Ibis Pereira
is a former police commander in
Rio. He says

23:41.654 --> 23:46.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the economic crisis in Brazil
has severely
crippled the policing program.
He also believes

23:47.026 --> 23:52.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the spike in violence is partly
tied to the
imminent arrival of the
Olympics.

23:52.097 --> 23:55.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COL. IBIS PEREIRA, Former Police
Commander
(through translator): Drug
trafficking is

23:55.134 --> 23:59.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a business that follows the same
logic of
trade around the world, supply
and demand.

23:59.905 --> 24:05.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there is an expectation of
profit, with
the presence of millions of
visitors to Rio,

24:05.477 --> 24:07.913 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and there is a moment of
weakness in the UPP
program.

24:07.946 --> 24:12.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LULU GARCIA-NAVARRO: Now many
are asking themselves
if there is a future for
pacification.

24:12.951 --> 24:15.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT MUGGAH, Igarape
Institute: There is
a sense in the police force and
within the

24:15.287 --> 24:18.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
public at large in Rio generally
that pacification
has hit a wall.

24:18.157 --> 24:21.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LULU GARCIA-NAVARRO: Robert
Muggah studies
security and development at the
Igarape Institute

24:21.460 --> 24:26.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Rio. He says there will be
tens of thousands
of security forces protecting
tourists and

24:26.465 --> 24:31.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
infrastructure during these
Olympics, twice
the size of those used in the
last Summer

24:31.537 --> 24:37.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Games. But that was London, and
this is Brazil,
one of the most unequal
countries on Earth.

24:37.376 --> 24:42.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And these Games, says Muggah,
will move resources
away from marginal communities.

24:42.181 --> 24:46.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT MUGGAH: Now, if you are a
white tourist
coming in from Europe or North
America, you're

24:46.385 --> 24:52.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to be absolutely safe.
However, if you
are a low-income black resident
from a favela

24:52.491 --> 24:55.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the lead-up to the Olympics,
and just afterward,
you are actually going to be
experience probably

24:55.828 --> 24:57.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a heightened sense of
insecurity.

24:57.696 --> 25:02.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LULU GARCIA-NAVARRO: Brazil has
promised the
Rio games will be safe. But
Olympic officials

25:02.034 --> 25:04.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
acknowledge it's not enough to
just secure
the games.

25:05.003 --> 25:08.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIO ANDRADA, Communications
Director, Rio
2014: What we need to push, and
we will do

25:08.974 --> 25:16.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so, is to have more security
before the Games,
and more security after the
games. We don't

25:16.048 --> 25:22.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
want the Games to be an island
of success
and perfection. We want the
Games to transform

25:22.054 --> 25:26.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rio, and to make Rio a safer
city in the years
to come.

25:26.425 --> 25:31.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LULU GARCIA-NAVARRO: What part
pacification
will play in that is unclear.
And that worries

25:31.730 --> 25:36.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Rodrigo da Silva, who supports
the program.
If the police pull out of the
favelas after

25:36.902 --> 25:39.304 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Olympics, he predicts the
worst.

25:39.338 --> 25:43.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RODRIGO DA SILVA (through
translator): There
will be more violence, more
violence in all

25:43.509 --> 25:48.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the communities because of the
fights between
the drug gangs, fights against
the police.

25:48.180 --> 25:52.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the end, the ones who will
pay for this
will be the residents, as
always.

25:52.384 --> 25:57.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LULU GARCIA-NAVARRO: As Rio de
Janeiro gets
ready for the Summer Games, da
Silva says

25:57.623 --> 26:03.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his Olympic dreams of a new life
shared by
many others are already out of
reach.

26:04.029 --> 26:14.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Lulu
Garcia-Navarro
NPR News, Rio de Janeiro.

26:14.706 --> 26:18.944 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

26:18.977 --> 26:24.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": why
a city seen
as an economic success story
