water's ever
been seen in the county in the
last 25 years.

27:43.662 --> 27:49.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: We see aerial
pictures sometimes
of horses being pulled off the
farm on to

27:49.334 --> 27:54.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
porches of homes. We just see
huge swathes
of rural area that just look
like large lakes

27:54.473 --> 27:56.675 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
now. How long until those drain?

27:56.708 --> 27:59.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFF BRAUN: Yes, it's a major
concern for
us.

27:59.978 --> 28:06.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The water that enters into the
city of Simonton,
which is the first town in Fort
Bend County

28:06.485 --> 28:15.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hat has the Brazos River,
there's probably
over 300 homes that have water
in them there.

28:15.093 --> 28:21.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, we also have the Texas
Animal Health
Commission going out to work
with some of

28:21.199 --> 28:28.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the ranchers out there because
they have cattle
that are in compromised
positions.

28:28.340 --> 28:34.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The water is flowing down the
river, not only
in rural areas, but into some of
our denser

28:34.479 --> 28:40.218 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
populated areas in the
Rosenberg-Richmond
area, and the water level is
going to crest

28:40.252 --> 28:47.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in a very long, slow time frame.
So we may
be looking at several days,
maybe even a week,

28:47.459 --> 28:51.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the water staying at the
level that it's
at right now, which is several
feet above

28:51.964 --> 28:54.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what would be the record crest.

28:54.399 --> 29:00.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Jeff, these --
these -- that
river snakes all the way across
your county,

29:00.272 --> 29:04.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and it has a lot of different
bends and probably
a lot of different elevations as
well.

29:04.343 --> 29:08.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are there particular areas
you're more concerned
about in the coming days, in the
coming weeks

29:08.347 --> 29:10.515 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that will be basically more
populated?

29:10.549 --> 29:16.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFF BRAUN: Well, the city of
Simonton and
Rosenberg were the first two
cities hit. And

29:16.188 --> 29:22.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
