concerned are you?

30:35.734 --> 30:38.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WALTER, Houston Office
of Emergency
Management: Well, obviously,
whenever we have

30:38.970 --> 30:43.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
significant rainfall events that
are back
to back the way that we have
seen the last

30:43.041 --> 30:46.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
couple of months, we're very
concerned about
the impacts that we could have
here in the

30:46.978 --> 30:48.814 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
city.

30:48.847 --> 30:54.319 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We have had a history of
rivering flooding
in our area, and so we are, as
always, continuing

30:54.352 --> 30:59.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to monitor that. Unfortunately,
it's just
the way that Houston was built.
This was a

30:59.524 --> 31:04.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
small town that was eclipsed by
the town of
Galveston when it was built.

31:04.329 --> 31:08.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, since then, we have just
had a lot
of development, we have had a
lot of building,

31:08.300 --> 31:13.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but, unfortunately, the way that
the Southeast
Texas area drains is through a
system of bayous.

31:13.605 --> 31:19.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if we do receive heavy
amounts of rain
in concentrated areas, that can
put a lot

31:19.411 --> 31:23.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
