it's falling,
and you can see the flooding is
happening

31:54.179 --> 31:56.047 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
upstream.

31:56.081 --> 31:59.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are you trying to prepare parts
of Houston
for possibly evacuations like
there are happening

31:59.417 --> 32:01.319 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Fort Bend County?

32:01.353 --> 32:05.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WALTER: So, our major
concern in the
city of Houston is not so much
the river flooding

32:05.824 --> 32:11.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that you see on the Brazos in
Fort Bend County
and in the other parts to the
west of the

32:11.863 --> 32:13.565 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
city.

32:13.598 --> 32:18.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our major concern is flash
flooding. That
usually is what impacts us here.
So, that's

32:18.403 --> 32:22.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really our concern. We're
looking at rainfall
totals. We're looking at the
location of where

32:22.374 --> 32:26.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that rain is going to fall. The
last three
federally declared disasters we
had, which

32:27.012 --> 32:32.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were all within one calendar
year of each
other, were all mostly related
to flash flooding

32:32.984 --> 32:37.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and water quickly rising and
water quickly
receding in our neighborhoods.

32:37.289 --> 32:42.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that's a little bit more
what we're concerned
about. We are monitoring the
Addicks and Barker

32:42.794 --> 32:46.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reservoirs, which are on the
west side of
Houston, which were built in the
late '30s

32:46.932 --> 32:51.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
following a catastrophic flood
in downtown
Houston. Those are holding up.
They are holding

32:51.770 --> 32:56.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the water. It is blocking some
roads in that
area, but those are doing the
job that they're

32:56.508 --> 32:58.276 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
doing.

32:58.310 --> 33:00.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers has been
working very closely to control
the amount

33:00.679 --> 33:05.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of water coming out of those
reservoirs as
it flows into a bayou that comes
right through

33:05.083 --> 33:06.852 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
downtown Houston.

33:06.885 --> 33:09.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Michael Walter
with the Office of Emergency
Management for

33:09.254 --> 33:14.159 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the city of Houston, thanks for
joining us.

33:14.192 --> 33:19.397 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WALTER: Thank you.

33:19.431 --> 33:26.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Tomorrow,
President Obama
will return to the first city he
visited after

33:26.137 --> 33:31.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
becoming president, Elkhart,
Indiana. It was
one of the worst-hit cities back
in 2009,

33:31.643 --> 33:35.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the president will be
delivering a speech
to tout what's been accomplished
since then.

33:35.280 --> 33:39.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He will sit down with our Gwen
Ifill for an
interview while he's there, and
then answer

33:39.651 --> 33:43.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
questions from residents in a
town hall special
we will be airing tomorrow
night.

33:43.855 --> 33:49.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It all comes during a tough
phase of the election
cycle, as the president seeks to
make a case

33:49.160 --> 33:50.495 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for his legacy.

33:50.528 --> 33:55.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
John Yang has the story.

33:55.033 --> 34:00.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: President Obama's
trip to Elkhart,
Indiana, tomorrow marks his
fifth visit since

34:00.105 --> 34:02.007 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he was a candidate in 2008.

34:02.040 --> 34:10.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2009, he went there to
announce $170 million
in federal stimulus money for
Elkhart County.

34:10.448 --> 34:16.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Elkhart is a city of about
50,000 people that
is known as the R.V. capital of
the world,

34:16.354 --> 34:20.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an industry on the rebound since
cratering
during the recession.

34:20.392 --> 34:27.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At its worst, unemployment
reached 20 percent.
Now it's 3.8 percent. Some give
the president

34:27.432 --> 34:29.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a certain amount of credit for
that.

34:29.234 --> 34:32.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY YOUNG, Elkhart, Indiana:
He's been doing
as best as he could do. It
wasn't perfect

34:32.737 --> 34:34.572 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
when he got in.

34:34.606 --> 34:38.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAM LAMBRIGHT, Elkhart, Indiana:
We have come
a long way. I think that the
economy is fairly

34:38.877 --> 34:42.781 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
good now. When it crashed in
'08, it was like
a ghost town around here.

34:42.814 --> 34:48.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Ed Neufeldt knows
that firsthand.
Laid off from his job in the
R.V. industry

34:48.286 --> 34:54.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in 2009, he now works four
part-time jobs,
including cleaning a doctor's
office. He's

34:54.225 --> 34:56.127 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
thankful there's enough work for
him.

34:56.161 --> 35:01.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ED NEUFELDT, Elkhart, Indiana:
If you want
a job in Elkhart County, there's
a job. You

35:01.166 --> 35:05.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can find a job. There's help
wanted signs
all over. Elkhart's doing great.

35:05.403 --> 35:10.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: It's quite a contract
to when we
last met him in 2009, when his
employer of

35:10.875 --> 35:12.744 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
32 years closed.

35:12.777 --> 35:19.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ED NEUFELDT: We were one of the
bigger corporations.
I thought we would be one of the
last to be

35:19.784 --> 35:21.720 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
around, but we weren't.

35:21.753 --> 35:26.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Despite the recovery,
Neufeldt
says there's a big divide
globally. Republicans

35:26.992 --> 35:28.960 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and Democrats can't get along.

35:28.994 --> 35:33.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ED NEUFELDT: They're angry.
That's the reason
so many people are voting for
Donald Trump.

35:33.865 --> 35:39.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They want to see a change. I
guess they feel
like government is just -- is
crooked.

35:39.471 --> 35:44.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, with President Obama
going to Elkhart
tomorrow to make his case for an
economic

35:44.275 --> 35:49.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
legacy, Neufeldt presents one of
the challenges
for the president and for the
Democratic candidates

35:49.781 --> 35:54.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who want to succeed it. Neufeldt
doesn't know
who he will vote for in the
fall.

35:54.753 --> 35:59.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when the "NewsHour" caught
up with locals
at the Memorial Day Parade, some
said they

35:59.290 --> 36:04.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were unhappy with the president,
like this
Trump supporter who listed his
complaints

36:04.229 --> 36:06.064 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with Mr. Obama.

36:06.097 --> 36:09.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KENNETH STORY, Elkhart, Indiana:
Lack of pride
of America and everybody getting
their feelings

36:09.401 --> 36:12.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
hurt over stupid things.

36:12.570 --> 36:18.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: In 2012, President
Obama lost Elkhart
County to Mitt Romney by a 2-1
wide margin

36:18.343 --> 36:24.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on his way to losing the state.
Although Elkhart's
fortunes and those of the R.V.
industry have

36:24.049 --> 36:30.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
made a dramatic turnaround, the
lingering
anxiety mirrors communities
across the country

36:30.221 --> 36:32.357 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
worried about their future.

36:32.390 --> 36:38.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm John
Yang.

36:39.030 --> 36:51.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Vermont is in
the midst
of the largest reorganization of
public schools

36:51.176 --> 36:56.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it has seen in the last 125
years. As many
other rural states have already
done, Vermont

36:56.548 --> 37:00.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wants to consolidate its many
small school
districts. But it's not
happening without

37:00.885 --> 37:02.687 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a fight.

37:02.720 --> 37:05.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent John
Tulenko of Education
Week has this report as part of
our weekly

37:05.623 --> 37:10.428 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
education series, Making the
Grade.

37:10.462 --> 37:25.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Vermont is a
collection of small
towns, many with just one or two
schools,

37:25.043 --> 37:28.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and where people feel they have
a say in their
children's education.

37:28.313 --> 37:30.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUZANNE HULL-PARENT, School
Board Member:
People have a very loud voice.
You know, some

37:30.815 --> 37:35.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people will say Montpelier
controls everything,
there's really not a lot of
voice left. Well,

37:35.787 --> 37:37.689 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
there is.

37:37.722 --> 37:40.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Like Suzanne
Hull-Parent, Vermonters
stay close with their schools
through their

37:40.825 --> 37:45.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
locally elected school boards.
There's one
for almost every town.

37:45.597 --> 37:49.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUZANNE HULL-PARENT: I have been
on the school
board for 12 years. I think when
you have

37:49.601 --> 37:53.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
local people living in the
community, making
the decisions about their school
the best

37:53.505 --> 37:58.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they can, it's going to be more
vested in
the good of that community.

37:58.076 --> 38:02.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Something else
about Vermont
schools, they're among the
smallest in the

38:02.614 --> 38:04.282 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
country.

38:04.315 --> 38:06.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUZANNE HULL-PARENT: You get
more individual
attention. I was blessed to have
that and

38:06.618 --> 38:11.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm blessed to have my children
have that.
And my daughter feels like she
has a voice.

38:11.222 --> 38:15.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm not sure, in a bigger
place, that
she would feel she had a voice.

38:15.860 --> 38:21.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Small schools and
local control
are in the DNA here. But that's
changing as

38:21.466 --> 38:28.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a result of a new state law
called Act 46.
It aims to consolidate Vermont's
school districts

38:28.306 --> 38:30.842 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and reduce their numbers by
half.

38:30.875 --> 38:37.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For now, communities can vote
yes to unification
and get tax breaks or say no and
lose a portion

38:37.115 --> 38:41.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of their school funding, and
risk being assigned
into a merger by the state.

38:41.152 --> 38:44.489 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: And I don't see how this
is helpful
for our children.

38:44.522 --> 38:47.792 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: But what if the vote is
no? What happens?

38:47.825 --> 38:51.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NICHOLS, Superintendent,
Franklin Northeast
Supervisory Union: Change is
hard. I think

38:51.729 --> 38:53.431 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
change is hard.

38:53.464 --> 38:58.336 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN TULENKO: For school
superintendent Jay
Nichols, change could help many
students.

38:58.369 --> 39:04.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nichols oversees five small
school districts
in Northern Vermont. Two of them
are neighboring

39:04.776 --> 39:08.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
districts, Richford and
Enosburg, and both
have high schools.

39:08.813 --> 39:15.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NICHOLS: Enosburg High
School, by Vermont
standards, a good-sized high
school, comprehensive

39:15.353 --> 39:21.359 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
school, offers a lot of
programming, you know,
seven or eight A.P. classes, has
a Junior

39:21.392 --> 39:28.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROTC program, which has saved
kids. Parents
will tell you, that has saved
their kids and

39:28.666 --> 39:33.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had them not drop out of school,
because of
Junior ROTC. Richford kids can't
go do that.

39:33.137 --> 39:38.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Richford High
School, in the
town next door, offers only two
A.P. classes,

39:38.309 --> 39:42.080 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not to mention no ROTC. The
reason for this
is size.

39:42.113 --> 39:45.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NICHOLS: It's a smaller
school, and it's
all about economies of scale.
And they offer

39:45.984 --> 39:48.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as much as they can for the size
that they
are.

39:48.152 --> 39:52.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Richford has about
150 students.
Enosburg has roughly double.

39:52.957 --> 39:56.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NICHOLS: If we become one
district, a
kid could take some classes in
Enosburg, some

39:56.361 --> 40:04.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
classes in Richford. If we share
the staff,
and share all the kids, we can
offer more.

40:04.168 --> 40:06.104 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's all.

40:06.137 --> 40:11.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: But Act 46 was
designed to accomplish
another goal, tax relief.
Two-thirds of the

40:11.643 --> 40:14.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
money Vermont spends on public
schools comes
from property taxes.

40:14.912 --> 40:18.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHAP SMITH, Vermont State
Speaker of the House:
It's a statewide property tax.
And when people

40:18.583 --> 40:21.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
get their bill, it tends to be a
big one.

40:21.853 --> 40:26.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: House Speaker Shap
Smith pushed
Act 46 through the state
legislature.

40:26.090 --> 40:31.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHAP SMITH: One of the things
that was driving
change was the fact that we have
declining

40:31.729 --> 40:38.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enrollment, and yet we have
increasing expenses.
Our student-to-teacher ratio is
one of the

40:38.770 --> 40:45.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lowest in the country, and that
is driving
the education costs for the last
15 to 20

40:45.843 --> 40:47.645 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
years.

40:47.679 --> 40:49.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NICHOLS: We have too many
adults for the
number of kids we have. That's
why we have

40:49.247 --> 40:52.317 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the most expensive education
system in the
United States.

40:52.350 --> 40:57.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Act 46 could lower
costs by
sharing staff and resources, but
the fear

40:57.522 --> 40:59.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is, some districts will go
farther.

40:59.390 --> 41:01.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SUZANNE HULL-PARENT: You will
see school closures.

41:01.559 --> 41:05.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: To Vermonters like
Suzanne Hull-Parent,
that would be significant.

41:05.963 --> 41:11.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUZANNE HULL-PARENT: You're
losing the heart
of many communities. That's
where they meet.

41:11.636 --> 41:15.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's where they have functions
that aren't
even school-related. That's
where families

41:15.106 --> 41:21.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in need get support services. I
think it just
is going to be devastating to
communities.

41:21.346 --> 41:24.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think they're going to change
the landscape
of Vermont with that.

41:24.849 --> 41:31.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Closing small
schools means
having to send students
elsewhere, to larger

41:31.089 --> 41:34.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
schools that offer more courses,
but may not
be better.

41:34.425 --> 41:38.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STUDENT: Like, people who go to
small schools,
like they -- when they graduate,
they leave

41:38.496 --> 41:41.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with something unique and
special that other
people don't have.

41:41.566 --> 41:46.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STUDENT: I came from a huge
school with a
lot of resources, and I came in
knowing that

41:46.637 --> 41:52.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there wasn't as many advanced
programs. But
connection is really important.
You know,

41:52.744 --> 41:55.480 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
there's a lot of support here.

41:55.513 --> 42:02.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Act 46 does
prohibit school
closings for at least four
years, but there

42:02.353 --> 42:05.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are other things Vermonters
would have to
give up right away.

42:05.189 --> 42:11.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NICHOLS: School choice in
Vermont. If
you live in a town that is a
tuition town,

42:11.763 --> 42:15.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you can go to school any place
you want, paid
for by the taxpayers.

42:15.199 --> 42:20.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Tuition towns are
those without
schools, often middle schools
and high schools.

42:20.204 --> 42:22.273 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Merging could cost them school
choice.

42:22.306 --> 42:27.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Today, we have the ability
to send our
kids to the best fit for them,
and we're going

42:27.578 --> 42:29.447 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to give that up.

42:29.480 --> 42:32.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Many of these
parents in Montgomery,
Vermont, send their children to
public and

42:32.717 --> 42:38.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
private high schools, including
this private
school in Canada, using school
choice vouchers

42:38.322 --> 42:44.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
worth some $14,000 each. In all,
it's about
a million dollars that's
projected to leave

42:44.529 --> 42:46.330 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the district.

42:46.364 --> 42:49.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAY NICHOLS: This is a huge
portion of the
budget that we can keep in our
local schools

42:49.967 --> 42:51.002 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and communities.

42:51.035 --> 42:52.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Could you offer
more A.P. courses?

42:52.303 --> 42:53.805 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAY NICHOLS: We certainly could.

42:53.838 --> 42:55.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: You don't think
there's a chance
that that million dollars...

42:55.840 --> 42:59.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUZANNE HULL-PARENT: Is just
going to infuse
