story.

44:19.690 --> 44:24.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Remind our
audience why you
ended up in Iraq in the first
place. You were

44:24.595 --> 44:30.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
working for a contractor, a
company that was
hired to be involved in
interrogating prisoners

44:30.301 --> 44:30.835 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of war.

44:30.868 --> 44:32.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ERIC FAIR: Right. Sure.

44:32.570 --> 44:34.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had been in the Army from 1990
to 2000.
I was an Arabic linguist. And I
had received

44:35.006 --> 44:38.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my discharge in 2000, when it
appeared that
there was no reason for an
Arabic linguist

44:38.776 --> 44:41.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be in the Army. Nothing
seemed to be going
on in the world.

44:41.045 --> 44:45.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I went back home to Bethlehem,
Pennsylvania,
became a police officer, and was
subsequently

44:45.583 --> 44:50.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
diagnosed with a heart condition
that ended
my career. And this was after
9/11. The war

44:50.354 --> 44:54.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Iraq was just beginning to
ramp up. The
invasion was over. Contracting
companies were

44:54.458 --> 44:58.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
desperate for employees in a
number of different
positions. And they were
desperate to get

44:58.229 --> 45:00.031 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people over as quickly as
possible.

45:00.064 --> 45:03.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I knew it was the one way
that I could
essentially sneak in without any
kind of health

45:03.634 --> 45:08.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
examination and get back into
that community.
I had supported the invasion and
I felt like

45:08.439 --> 45:11.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I had an obligation, because of
that support,
to be a part of it.

45:11.275 --> 45:14.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What did you
think you were
going to be doing when you went
to Iraq, and

45:14.979 --> 45:17.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then how did that compare with
what you found
yourself in the middle of?

45:17.915 --> 45:22.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIC FAIR: My experience with a
war in the
Middle East had been, like many
Americans,

45:22.520 --> 45:24.221 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with the first Gulf War.

45:24.255 --> 45:28.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the impression that I had
was that
we -- there would be thousands
of Iraqi troops

45:28.192 --> 45:32.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
surrendering, being brought back
to the rear,
and then essentially debriefed.
And so we

45:32.863 --> 45:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would have talked to them about
the units
that they were in and the
strength of those

45:35.666 --> 45:39.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
units, things like the kind of
weapons they
had or the systems -- that
weapons systems,

45:40.004 --> 45:43.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to gauge just how committed and
how strong
these troops were.

45:43.441 --> 45:47.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We had not anticipated doing
interrogations
or being part of a prisoner of
war camp in

45:47.712 --> 45:53.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iraq and surrounded by combat.
And so we were
driven out to Abu Ghraib and
essentially started

45:53.384 --> 45:57.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
work the next day. And much of
it was really
more associated with law
enforcement.

45:57.288 --> 46:01.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was the idea of deciding
whether or not
someone was guilty or why they
had been captured,

46:01.792 --> 46:08.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or if they should stay in
custody. The insurgency
was just beginning to ramp up at
point. Mortars

46:08.466 --> 46:12.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were definitely coming into Abu
Ghraib, but
soldiers were being killed by
IEDs. The death

46:12.703 --> 46:14.472 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
count was continuing to rise.

46:14.505 --> 46:19.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The idea that the insurgency or
the war was
going to end was clear to us
that it wasn't.

46:19.443 --> 46:23.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so there was an absolute
need for more
intelligence information to
figure out what

46:23.648 --> 46:25.483 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was going wrong.

46:25.516 --> 46:30.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You write in a
lot of detail,
graphic detail, about what you
saw, how people

46:30.721 --> 46:38.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were treated. Was it a matter of
not expecting
this? What do you think,
ultimately, drove

46:38.462 --> 46:40.197 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you to want to get out of there?

46:40.231 --> 46:43.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIC FAIR: I think I was aware
right away
that, morally, this was
difficult, the kind

46:43.801 --> 46:46.237 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of treatment that prisoners were
receiving.

46:46.270 --> 46:51.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in terms of the legal
issues surrounding
it, it was policy. And this is
essentially

46:51.909 --> 46:56.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what we were supposed to be
doing. The vast
majority of us, as contractors,
were prior

46:56.047 --> 46:59.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
soldiers. And so we felt a
commitment to the
people in uniform and to
ourselves and to

46:59.950 --> 47:01.719 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
our community to do these
things.

47:01.752 --> 47:05.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I lasted about two months doing
interrogations.
And then eventually I took
another position

47:05.589 --> 47:10.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
back in Baghdad that wasn't
involved in interrogations.
But I knew then, even though
that I had supported

47:10.728 --> 47:14.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the war, that the invasion was
wrong. There
clearly were no chemical weapons
in Iraq.

47:14.965 --> 47:18.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And much of the narrative that
we heard about
what was going on there simply
wasn't true.

47:18.436 --> 47:23.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So much of the
book, Eric Fair,
is about how this affected you
and continues

47:23.274 --> 47:25.076 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to affect you.

47:25.109 --> 47:27.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIC FAIR: The process started
in late 2006,
in which I knew I needed to
start writing

47:27.978 --> 47:29.914 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about some of the things that I
had done.

47:29.947 --> 47:34.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I knew that the only way to
do that effectively
was to write about my own role.
And so it

47:34.385 --> 47:39.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wasn't to be a policy pundit and
talk about
the administration or about the
legal issues

47:39.056 --> 47:43.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
surrounding it, but I needed to
provide an
honest account of my own
narrative.

47:43.327 --> 47:46.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, at the time when I started
writing, I
wasn't calling this torture.
That's something

47:46.764 --> 47:51.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I only processed recently and
begun to realize
that, absolutely, the things we
did is torture.

47:51.302 --> 47:53.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so there have been
consequences for me.

47:53.204 --> 47:56.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I recognize that the people
who were on
the other side of the table in
the interrogation

47:56.173 --> 47:58.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
booths are the ones who suffered
the true
consequences.

47:58.576 --> 48:00.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do you want
to come out
of this book?

48:00.578 --> 48:06.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIC FAIR: Well, I think, like
any writer,
it's some sort of hope for a
change of the

48:06.417 --> 48:08.385 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
narrative.

48:08.419 --> 48:10.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have a presidential -- we
have presidential
candidates who are now talking
about water-boarding

48:11.021 --> 48:14.859 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and talking about other
aggressive techniques.
We have the director of the CIA
suggesting

48:14.892 --> 48:20.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that his men or his employees
wouldn't water-board,
which is encouraging, but also
very disturbing

48:20.397 --> 48:26.036 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in terms of -- it's a
recognition of where
we can go, and we can still go
back to where

48:26.070 --> 48:27.805 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
we were.

48:27.838 --> 48:30.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, we may even go back to
something
-- something far worse. So,
there needs to

48:30.508 --> 48:35.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be an honest narrative about not
only what
this does to certainly the
personnel that

48:35.913 --> 48:39.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we will put in these positions,
but to the
-- the kind of things that it
does to the

48:39.383 --> 48:41.085 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
